If $$\left| {\matrix{
   a &amp; {{a^2}} &amp; {1 + {a^3}}  \cr 
   b &amp; {{b^2}} &amp; {1 + {b^3}}  \cr 
   c &amp; {{c^2}} &amp; {1 + {c^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$ and vectors $$\left( {1,a,{a^2}} \right),\,\,$$
<br><br/>$$\left( {1,b,{b^2}} \right)$$ and $$\left( {1,c,{c^2}} \right)\,$$ are non-coplanar, then the product $$abc$$ equals :

questions.solution:
$$\left| {\matrix{
   a &amp; {{a^2}} &amp; {1 + {a^3}}  \cr 
   b &amp; {{b^2}} &amp; {1 + {b^3}}  \cr 
   c &amp; {{c^2}} &amp; {1 + {c^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$
<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left| {\matrix{
   a &amp; {{a^2}} &amp; 1  \cr 
   b &amp; {{b^2}} &amp; 1  \cr 
   c &amp; {{c^2}} &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   a &amp; {{a^2}} &amp; {{a^3}}  \cr 
   b &amp; {{b^2}} &amp; {{b^3}}  \cr 
   c &amp; {{c^2}} &amp; {{c^3}}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$
<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left( {1 + abc} \right)\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; a &amp; {{a^2}}  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; {{b^2}}  \cr 
   1 &amp; c &amp; {{c^2}}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$
<br><br>As $$\,\,\,\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; a &amp; {{a^2}}  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; {{b^2}}  \cr 
   1 &amp; c &amp; {{c^2}}  \cr 

 } } \right| \ne 0$$  (given condition) 
<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$abc=-1$$

